### Description

This adds a new p2p discovery module to the compact block filters blockchain implementation in BDK.  The high level idea is for a wallet that wants to be a light client using compact block filters to not need to specify an explicit peer to sync the chain.

The current implementation starts with the DNS seeds and performs a network search using `GetAddr` messages with connected peers.  It builds a directory with successfully connected addresses and their services flag.  It caches this directory to the filesystem to speed up discovery on subsequent startups of the wallet.

Currently there is no way to extract a peer or set of peers from this directory but that is a good next step.

It currently uses a configurable amount of worker threads to perform the crawl and I recommend spawning a thread to run the `manage` control loop that spawns the workers and handles worker messages.

The high level structs and architecture looks like this:

`AddressManager` -- the top level struct that gets instantiated to start everything.  The manager holds the directory, a shared list of addresses being searched, and channels for messaging between the worker threads and the manager.

`AddressDirectory` -- Right now it holds two indexes, one for cbf enabled addresses and the other for the rest.  Each index is a `VecDeque<NodeAddress>` where a `NodeAddress` is just an SocketAddr and ServicesFlag.  The indexes probably should not be VecDeque's, this was just easier for serializing from this to the filesystem and back into a the same structure the workers use for managing a list of addresses to search.  

`AddressDiscovery` -- a struct wrapped in Arc<Mutex> for sharing between worker threads.  It contains a list of addresses to be searched and which addresses have already been visited.  

`AddressWorker` -- a struct representing a network crawler worker.  it maintains a reference to the AddressDiscovery struct and a channel for sending messages to the AddressManager.

`DiscoveryProgress` -- a trait for receiving progress updates from the address manager.  this is modeled after the Progress trait used to track progress when syncing the blockchain. I provided implementations for noop, logger, and Sender<DiscoveryData>.

The changes to `peer` were to prevent the workers from getting stuck on a particular peer.  The current implementation blocks indefinitely when connecting and when receiving responses.  I added a connect_with_timeout and also changed the verack and version messages to timeout after 1 second.  We probably don't want to keep it exactly like this.  It might not even make sense to use the Peer struct when doing the discovery.  It also might make sense to rewrite some of the peer network messaging logic in a way that doesn't block and expect a single response.

Some example code if you want to try running an AddressManager search with BDK from this fork:

```
use std::thread;
use bdk::blockchain::compact_filters::{AddressManager, log_discovery_progress};
use bdk::bitcoin::network::constants::Network;
use simple_logger::SimpleLogger;

fn main() -> Result<(), bdk::Error> {
    SimpleLogger::new().init().unwrap();
    
    let network = Network::Bitcoin;
    let mut address_manager = AddressManager::new(network, "cache.json".to_string(), 8);
    
    let manager_handle = thread::spawn(move || {
        address_manager.manage(log_discovery_progress());
    });

    manager_handle.join().unwrap();
    Ok(())
}
```


